<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06242107 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06242107 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  A four-year measles epidemic that has preyed mostly on unvaccinated inner-citychildren, killing scores of youngsters across the country, has ebbed sharplyin most states, federal health officials said Wednesday. Though they warned itwas too soon to declare the epidemic in full control, they were encouraged bya sharp drop in cases -- especially in California, the hot spot a year ago.The worst state now is New York, which accounts for nearly half the 7,957cases reported this year. Just nine states reported new cases in 1991.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PROGRESS NOTED IN LONG FIGHT AGAINST MEASLES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  National News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910829  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  94  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, August 29, 199100242107,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>